    <p>	
	What dBm Sensitivity Means:

    Decibels relative to a milliwatt (dBm) is a logarithmic unit 
	measuring power, where 0 dBm is 1 milliwatt (mW).</p> 
	<p>	
	Negative dBm values indicate power less than 1 mW 
	(e.g., -30 dBm is 0.001 mW or 1 microwatt).</p>	
	<p>	
    Receiver Capability: A receiver's sensitivity is the minimum
	input signal strength it needs to accurately decode data, often
	measured at a specific bit error rate (BER).</p>	
	<p>	
    The Scale: Values closer to zero (less negative) are 
	stronger signals; values further from zero (more negative) 
	are weaker signals.</p>	
    <p>
	Interpreting dBm Sensitivity Values:

    Better Sensitivity (More Negative): A capable receiver with
	-96 dBm sensitivity can go twice as far as a -90 dBm  
	because it can detect weaker signals.</p>
	
    <p>
    Why It Matters:

    Range: Higher sensitivity (more negative dBm) allows for longer
	communication distances.
    Interference Immunity: A sensitive receiver can distinguish weak
	desired signals from background noise, less breakup, improving
	reliability.
    System Design: Balancing transmit power and receiver sensitivity
	is key for effective FPV.</p>
